post_text:
Thank you for your patience this morning as we worked with our service provider to resolve technical issues with StudentVUE. Less than an hour into the learning day, the vendor added resources at the connection point to increase access for students. The issue now appears to be fixed.

Department of Technology staff will continue to monitor the system and student access throughout the day to troubleshoot as needed. As of 9:15 a.m., more than 9,000 people were successfully signed into the system.

Thank you for your patience this morning as we worked with our service provider to resolve technical issues with StudentVUE. Less than an hour into the learning day, the vendor added resources at the connection point to increase access for students. The issue now appears to be fixed.

Department of Technology staff will continue to monitor the system and student access throughout the day to troubleshoot as needed. As of 9:15 a.m., more than 9,000 people were successfully signed into the system.

post_text:
WJCC Schools is currently experiencing problems with StudentVUE, the system used for remote learning. We are working with the service provider to troubleshoot the issue now. At this time, it is unclear whether this is a local issue or part of a larger access problem as students across Virginia begin school.

We apologize for the inconvenience and will update you once the issue is fixed. In the meantime, students should try to log in periodically to access classes.

post_text:
Today we start the 2020-21 school year strong because WJCC Schools staff stepped up to the challenge of creating engaging and safe ways to learn, teach, and work no matter what we encounter this year. All week, we’re honoring these amazing Heroes of Hope who make our Return to Learn possible.

Let’s start by thanking the 250 teachers who developed digital content for more than 190 K-12 courses in preparation for remote learning. Providing consistent curriculum and resources across the division allows teachers and instructional staff space to focus on what is most important- students. Read more at http://wjccschools.org/heroesofhope

post_text: “On behalf of the school board and the entire WJCC Schools family, I would like to offer our heartfelt sympathy to the Hornsby family. Lois S. Hornsby was an unwavering advocate for public education and the arts in our community. She personified the motto “service before self,” and we are all deeply saddened by her passing. We are proud that one of our schools bears the name of this great woman and we remain committed to the issues of equality, bridging racial gaps, and the recruitment of minority teachers that Mrs. Hornsby championed throughout her life.” – Lisa Ownby, School Board Chair
text: “On behalf of the school board and the entire WJCC Schools family, I would like to offer our heartfelt sympathy to the Hornsby family. Lois S. Hornsby was an unwavering advocate for public education and the arts in our community. She personified the motto “service before self,” and we are all deeply saddened by her passing. We are proud that one of our schools bears the name of this great woman and we remain committed to the issues of equality, bridging racial gaps, and the recruitment of minority teachers that Mrs. Hornsby championed throughout her life.” – Lisa Ownby, School Board Chair

post_text: We can't stop celebrating our incredible Class of 2020! Check out this great video from our friends at JPixx.
shared_text:
WWW.JPIXX.COM
WJCC 2020 Graduation Parade

Jpixx
July 10 at 5:43 PM ·

With smiles on and horns blaring, the staff and faculty of Williamsburg-James City County Public Schools organized a special send off for the class of 2020! Between Lafayette High School (Virginia) , Jamestown High School , and Warhill High School, the graduates paraded down Duke of Gloucester Street in Colonial Williamsburg. Teachers, friends, and family cheered and waved, from the streetside, as decorated cars revved their engines along the pavement!

It was a fantastic event and a great way to let these seniors send their farewells in fashion! Congratulations to the class of 2020!

Matt & Nicole

post_text: As we begin the 2-week closure to help combat coronavirus, we want to thank our incredible community for your flexibility and understanding as events escalated. A special “thank you” to our teachers, curriculum and instruction leaders and administrators who worked tirelessly to create take home learning activities for students. It also goes without saying that our custodians and operations staff are heroes for their efforts to keep our buildings clean and disinfected. At times of turmoil, we are reminded of all that can be accomplished when we work together to support young people. With gratitude and wishes for good health, THANK YOU. #WeAreWJCC

post_text:
Good morning WJCC Schools families and staff.

This is school superintendent Olwen Herron with an important message about safety.

This morning, a school volunteer at Matthew Whaley Elementary contacted us to say that she has tested positive for coronavirus.

We are working now to contact the small number of families whose child may have come in contact with this person.

Obviously, this news is upsetting to all of us. Out of an abundance of caution, we will close Matthew Whaley at 10:30 this morning. All other schools are operating on their normal schedule.

We continue to be in contact with the health department and we will make an announcement about future school operations for the division later today.

post_text: Thank you to William & Mary's Fraternity Kappa Sigma for donating $1,000 to Matchsticks BBQ Co.'s Lunch Box Program to help pay down the student lunch debt for all WJCC Schools! Matchsticks BBQ began the Lunch Box Program in June and has previously contributed more than $1,200 to pay student lunch debt. Kappa Sigma Philanthropy Chair Caleb Rogers, inspired to support the program after reading a news article about student lunch debt and Matchsticks BBQ’s efforts, presented Nicole Sileno with the donation on behalf of his fraternity. #WeAreWJCC

"Create a routine that gets your family ready for school
The start of a new school year is exciting, but it often means families must make a few adjustments. This year, decide on some basics for your school-year routine. Set a regular homework time. Create a chart of your child's daily tasks that he can use as a reminder until they become habits. Post a calendar and have everyone write down their activities. Then review it each week with your child and plan ahead. #WeAreWJCC
"
